{
    "question_stem": "Consider the quadratic function given by \\(y = x(4-x)\\).",
    "parts": [
        {
            "part_label": "a",
            "question_text": "State the key features of the graph of this function, including its shape, and any intercepts with the axes.",
            "solution_text": "The equation \\(y = x(4-x)\\) represents a quadratic function. Expanding it gives \\(y = 4x - x^2 = -x^2 + 4x\\).  Since the coefficient of \\(x^2\\) is negative, the graph is an inverted parabola (n-shaped).  \n\nTo find the x-intercepts, we set \\(y = 0\\):\n\\(x(4-x) = 0\\)\nThis gives \\(x = 0\\) or \\(x = 4\\). Thus, the x-intercepts are (0,0) and (4,0).\n\nTo find the y-intercept, we set \\(x = 0\\):\n\\(y = 0(4-0) = 0\\)\nThus, the y-intercept is (0,0), which we already identified as one of the x-intercepts. Therefore the graph passes through the origin."
        }
    ],
